com.infinitydb.map.air

Class AirConcurrentMap<K,V>

    All Implemented Interfaces:
    VisitableMap<K,V>, java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentMap<K,V>, java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentNavigableMap<K,V>, java.util.Map<K,V>, java.util.NavigableMap<K,V>, java.util.SortedMap<K,V>

    public class AirConcurrentMap<K,V>
extends com.infinitydb.map.wrapper.DefaultAbstractConcurrentNavigableMap<K,V>
implements java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, VisitableMap<K,V>
    AirConcurrentMap is an extended multi-core ConcurrentNavigableMap and is faster and more memory efficient than any standard Java library Map and others for a wide range of use cases, especially large Map sizes.

    AirConcurrentMap's memory efficiency becomes the best above a certain break-even point in size - approximately 1K Entries. This is true because there is a minimum allocation of one chunk. Iterators are faster at almost any size, and there is an additional even faster MapVisitor and ThreadedMapVisitor feature. AirConcurrentMap is a drop-in replacement for any standard Map. For graphs see AirConcurrentMap_Performance_Testing.pdf in the root archive directory or www.boilerbay.com/docs/AirConcurrentMap_Performance_Testing.pdf and http://www.boilerbay.com.

    Increased memory efficiency allows 30% to 50% more Entries than ConcurrentSkipListMap, which is AirConcurrentMap's only serious ordered competitor, and memory efficiency grows to be better than that for any other Maps after a threshold size on the order of 1K entries. The memory efficiency of an AirConcurrentMap grows to nearly the theoretical maximum of two references per Entry.

    The put, get, and remove speeds are about 90% higher than ConcurrentSkipListMap, and are almost the theoretical maximum speed for an ordered Map, which is the key comparison time times log2(n). Many other operations, such as higherKey() and other ordered retrievals plus operations like containsKey() have the same log2(n) performance. This includes many ordered and unordered key-based search operations on the keySet() and entrySet() and values() collection.

    For iteration of the keySet, entrySet and values, ConcurrentSkipListMap is somewhat better than AirConcurrentMap for small Maps, but above a small size threshold of about 10 to 1K Entries, AirConcurrentMap takes the lead, reaching about two to four times as fast. AirConcurrentMap iterates faster than all other standard Maps for all entry counts, reaching roughly four times faster with larger Maps. Iteration is even faster if the block size is increased.

    Additional scanning speed is available via MapVisitor, and threaded scanning via ThreadedMapVisitor, and in the future, possibly remote visiting over multiple hosts.

    AirConcurrentMap is multi-core, with approximately linear scaling. Concurrency increases with Map size, and it begins at about 1K to 2K Entries for relatively well distributed keys, and The linear scaling means that as the system core count increases, performance increases accordingly. This means that when multiple Threads concurrently access or modify the map, there will be minimal interference between them, so each thread executes as if it were the only thread using the map. Scaling of thread count is also good, allowing hundreds of threads to use an AirConcurrentMap with a relatively small rolloff in speed with a given core count.

    it is suggested to use some kind of ConcurrentMap such as AirConcurrentMap in all places in any system that uses threading, because otherwise accidental concurrent modification of the Map by multiple threads can destroy the Map's internal consistency and create bugs that rarely manifest and are difficult to understand and reproduce. Also, non-concurrent Maps return wrong results in unpredictable ways for a concurrent single-writer and any number of readers.

    Note the constructors with block length parameters and the JVM parameter com.infinitydb.air.block.length which controls the default block lengths. This is the default for AirConcurrentMaps constructed without explicit block lengths. It is a positive integer. Iterator speed, for example, benefits from blocks that are longer than the default, but the memory efficiency threshold moves up. The default is good in general. The default is usually 500, but scanning is faster for blocks up to about 2K, over a broad optimum. Also note the setRetainFreedSpace() method which is used to force the keeping of space freed via remove() and clear() in a pool for somewhat faster re-use of a particular Map by put().

    Limitations:

    • The initial implementations of AirConcurrentMap use a simplified algorithm for submaps which is slower for iteration - about log2(n).
    • Because AirConcurrentMap implements the ConcurrentNavigableMap interface, it is compatible only with Java 1.6 and later.
    • AirConcurrentMap has a minimum memory usage per instance that is larger than some other Maps - about 5KB.
    • Visiting via ThreadedMapVisitor: each threaded visiting locks the Map. The advantage of this is extremely high performance.
    • The number of threads is usually the number of processors minus one. Leaving a processor free allows the system to function normally during the scan. (Windows freezes up if all cores are 100% busy, under Windows 8.1 at least). In the future, a scheduling interface may allow more control of the Threads. A complete long visitation often takes only milliseconds, so the latency of other operations is not heavily affected.

    • Method Detail

      • setRetainFreedSpace

        public void setRetainFreedSpace(boolean isRetainingFreedSpace)
        By default, isRetainingFreedSpace is false, but if set true, the AirConcurrentMap keeps a pool of its internal space as space is freed by clear() or remove(). The preserved space will be used for future allocations, possibly increasing speed for put() and so on. The improvement depends on the efficiency of the garbage collector of the JVM and whether GC is already overloaded in a particular application and GC cycles are to be avoided. This flag can be changed at will, but the free pool never shrinks. To get back all of the space, construct a new Map.
        Parameters:
        isRetainingFreedSpace - set retaining free space mode

      • size

        public int size()
        Return the size of the Map.

        Note that this does not just return an internal count of the entries (which can be slow to maintain in a multicore concurrent environment) but instead iterates internal structures quickly. However, it should be orders of magnitude faster than a simple iteration of the entries one-by-one. If the size() of the AirConcurrentMap is being used only to detect the empty case, then it will be faster for a very large Map to use isEmpty(). The size() will probably begin to slow down compared to isEmpty() when the Map reaches many hundreds or thousands of entries.

        The count cannot be atomic because it iterates, so concurrent modification of the Map during the internal iteration will produce a result that does not reflect the actual size at any particular instant. For example, concurrent put and get that affect entries whose keys come before or after the internal iterator will affect the result differently. The Map.size() interface does not define the behavior of the size() method while the Map is changing, and our comments here do not represent a guarantee of future behavior but are intended only as a note pointing out the issue.

        Note that this is not currently guaranteed to be atomic, but an effort has been made to keep it very fast. It takes linear time.

        Specified by:
        size in interface java.util.Map<K,V>
        Overrides:
        size in class com.infinitydb.map.wrapper.AbstractConcurrentNavigableMap<K,V>
        Returns:
        number of entries in the map, not necessarily at a particular instant in time if the map is concurrently changing. Such dynamic behavior is undefined by Map.size().

      • clear

        public void clear()
        Clear the Map.

        The free space is not GC'ed unless isRetainingFreedSpace is false, which is the default. By preventing the GC, the free space is kept in a pool for immediate re-use by the Map without construction in case more puts populate the Map again. When the Map is finally GC'ed itself, the saved free space in the pool is freed as well.

        This executes in linear time, but is orders of magnitude faster than iteratively removing entries. It is atomic to the extent that there is a moment in time when the map is completely empty, even though other concurrent modification operations may be in progress.

        Specified by:
        clear in interface java.util.Map<K,V>
